sathomas:
Full context on [github](https://github.com/sathomas/3akai-ux/blob/docpreview/node_modules/oae-core/documentpreview/js/documentpreview.js), but the code itself is simple enough.

Either:

```
$.ajax({
    url: '/path/to/base.css',
    dataType: 'text'
})
.done(function(response) {
    var domNode = domNode || document.createElement('style');
    domNode.type = 'text/css';
    if (domNode.styleSheet) {
        domNode.styleSheet.cssText = response;
    } else {
        domNode.appendChild(document.createTextNode(response));
    }
    var head = document.head || document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0];
    head.appendChild(domNode);
})
```

Or:

```
$('head').append('<link rel="stylesheet" href="/path/to/base.css"/>');
```

Both will expose the bug in the stylesheet. Apparently, when Safari or Chrome (I haven't checked other browsers) retrieves the referenced style sheet, it converts all CSS selectors to lower case. You can see from the developer console that the server delivers the file with mixed case:

![screen shot 2013-10-22 at 8 50 07 am](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/1731910/1381130/fb0447e8-3b19-11e3-95a2-b6f0f19e863f.png)

But when the browser determines which selectors to apply, it's converted all selectors to lowercase, which again is evident from the developer console.

![screen shot 2013-10-22 at 8 49 10 am](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/1731910/1381232/4f4e1624-3b1c-11e3-8141-c2c2a1530b66.png)

As a result, even though the image has a class of `bi`, it's getting the CSS rules for both `.bi` and `.Bi` and the `top` property is getting set to `0` which, as the original screen shot demonstrates, places the image in the wrong place on the page.
. I sure wish we didn't have to support IE9 (and IE10 once IE11 is released). Alas, that's not possible for us just yet. One change you might consider is adding a `1px` top and left border with a color of `#ccc`. Here's what that looks like in IE9 (the example on the right):

![border-ie](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/1731910/1448126/4d3c73c0-4252-11e3-8ff1-c332c43208be.png)

And it seems reasonable in other browsers as well:

![border-ok](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/1731910/1448133/586d25b4-4252-11e3-8083-e35ed8624b50.png)

It's definitely not perfect, but maybe a decent compromise.

Here's a [blog post](http://blog.sathomas.me/post/css-box-shadows-and-browser-differences) on the issue that you can reference if you like.

Stephen
. Internet Explorer sure is painful. Unfortunately IE-only style sheets won't work for version 10 (and presumably version 11 which I'm guessing has the same implementation of box shadow). I haven't been able to think of an alternative to borders, but I'll do some more experimenting and maybe something will come up. 
. FWIW, the problem is definitely present in Chrome 31 on both OS X 10.9.1 and Windows 7. On both systems the display is identical. Interestingly, the problem is not present in Chrome 31 on Android 4.1. (Checking the latter on my cheap Huawei smartphone was definitely an adventure ;^)
. @coolwanglu, you're definitely right on both counts:
1. The `<span>` rule in `base.css` is the most problematic, as that will almost certainly conflict with other elements on a page. The suggestion to add a `t` class will definitely help.
2. Adding a unique class to all of the CSS selectors will definitely increase the size of the styles. As a check, I looked at the [Scientific Paper](http://coolwanglu.github.io/pdf2htmlEX/demo/demo.html) example as something of a worst case. The total number of selectors in all three `<style>` blocks is 2292, so adding a 12-byte class selector to all of them (e.g. `.pdf2htmlex ' including the trailing space) will increase the file size by about 27,500 bytes.

OTOH, there are some additional factors to consider:
1. The total size of the example (without the unique class) is about 1.8 Mbytes, so adding the class only increases the total size by 1.5%. (For smaller and less complex documents, the increase would be a greater percentage.)
2. Any good web server will be using gzip compression which reduces the absolute size of the files (including the additional class selector) by at least a factor of 2. (Even with compression, though, there would still be a significant increase, e.g. 14KB in the example.)
3. There are some other rules in the `base.css` file that are fairly common in web pages (e.g. `#sidebar` or  `.loading-indicator`) and could well conflict with a larger web page.
4. Even for the abbreviated classes that pdf2htmlex uses, it's impossible to know for certain that there won't be conflicts. I suppose the worst-case possibility would be a web page that wanted to display two translated PDF documents side-by-side. In that case nearly all the style rules would conflict.

I can't read C++ well enough to assess how much extra effort it would take to add a command-line option to include (or not) an additional CSS selector, but if that's feasible, it might be the most straightforward way to deal with all concerns. (Well, it would at least leave the decision up to the implementation).
. The change `.t span` is definitely a big help; it resolves the most obvious issues. I'm not sure I'd recommend a compile time option since, as you note, that wouldn't completely address the problem. The simplest approach might be to just post-process the css files by running them through LESS.
. Although I haven't looked at the code, I can guess the reason for this. When the CSS scale transform is applied to content, the browser still uses the natural height (e.g. the height before zooming) when calculating the size of the elements. To counteract this problem, you can set the height (and width) explicitly. The approach we used is to set the width as a percentage (e.g. 50% zoom sets `scale(0.5)` and `width: 50%`) and adjust the `top-margin` of subsequent content. Implementation [here]((https://github.com/sathomas/3akai-ux/tree/docpreview/node_modules/oae-core/documentpreview).

Here's the relevant code:

```
var zoomPages = function() {
    // keep track of how much margin for next page
    var nextMargin = CONTENT_PAGE_SPACING;

    _.every(pages, function(page) {
        // only process pages that have content
        if (page.$el) {
            // Scale the page
            page.$el.css({
                'margin-top': nextMargin + 'px',
                'transform': 'scale(' + state.zoomLevel + ')',
                'width': 100 / state.zoomLevel + '%'
            });
            // Cache the extra margin that was added
            page.marginTop = nextMargin;

            // When zooming in(/out) one page, we need to move the following
            // page down(/up) because the browser won't do it automatically
            nextMargin = (page.height * state.zoomLevel - page.height) +
                CONTENT_PAGE_SPACING * state.zoomLevel;

            // Return true to continue to next page
            return true;

        } else {
            // Return false to skip remaining pages
            return false;
        }
    });
}
```
. Me neither. Just guessing, but I think Homebrew cleans up everything on a failed installation. I'm hoping the problem can be reproduced with a standard Unix build when trying to use the latest poppler.
